entries.name: I Love LA
entries.description: Funny woman Rachel Sennott is bringing her wonderfully warped sense of humor to HBO Max with a weekly scripted comedy series about an ambitious LA friend group. Created, written, and starring Sennott, the eight-episode season appears to lampoon (and maybe celebrate a little?) Los Angeles’ perpetual hustle culture as its main cast attempts to navigate life and love in La La Land. Not only does the show have an iconic core cast (Odessa A'zion and Josh Hutcherson, hello), it also boasts an impressive roster of guests like Leighton Meester, Quenlin Blackwell, Elijah Wood, and Froy Gutierrez, among others. — Adrienne

entries.name: Frankenstein
entries.description: With his heart on his sleeve and a devilish grin on his lips, Mexican auteur Guillermo del Toro explained that adapting Mary Shelley’s masterwork into a personal fable of fathers and sons is “like marrying a widow – you have to respect the memory of the late husband. But on Saturday, you gotta party on.” Oscar Isaac plays the bad dad/mad scientist Dr. Victor Frankenstein, while Jacob Elordi absolutely disappears, physically and vocally, into the role of del Toro’s misunderstood monster, whose reanimated tissue is the beating heart of this extremely earnest and epic morality play. Not to mention, the visual spectacle of del Toro’s rip-roaring retelling hits harder than the Creature’s super-powered punches that literally break a man’s back in half during the film’s arctic ass-kicking of an opening. — Alex

entries.name: Predator: Badlands
entries.description: Over three films, director Dan Trachtenberg has been reinventing the Predator franchise, pitting the alien hunter against Comanche warriors in Prey; battling Vikings, samurai, and WWII pilots in the animated Predator: Killer of Killers; and now flipping the script and making the predator our hero. In Predator: Badlands, an outcast predator (Demetrius Schuster-Koloamatangi) seeks redemption through a big game hunt on a hostile planet. Helping him is a Weyland-Yutani synth played by Elle Fanning, fueling rumors that we'll be seeing another direct crossover between the Alien and Predator franchises before long. — James

entries.name: Pluribus
entries.description: Vince Gilligan returns to both Albuquerque and his sci-fi roots with Pluribus, his new and twisty take on the pandemic genre. The intriguing premise follows Carol (Rhea Seehorn) as the only person immune to a virus that causes uncontrollable optimism and happiness. With the tagline, The most miserable person on Earth must save the world from happiness, I can't wait to see how this one plays out. I mean, would a world full of happiness and optimism be a bad thing? The series marks a reunion between Gilligan and Better Call Saul star Seehorn, and has been greenlit for two seasons before its debut. Given Gilligan's track record and Apple TV's track record of leaning into high-quality sci-fi programming, my expectations are high for this one.  —Vanessa

entries.name: Die My Love
entries.description: Seems like Jennifer Lawrence is gripped by a condition that SSRIs can’t help in this hopefully awesome psychological drama from Lynne Ramsay, the director’s first film in eight years. Lawrence and Robert Pattinson are a couple who make that classic movie mistake of retreating to a quiet life in a remote locale, where things go off the rails tout suite. Every Ramsay film is divisive; she’s an uncompromising filmmaker, meant as the highest of praise. If Die My Love’s hysterics ultimately aren’t your bag, perhaps you, like me, can remain happy for two actors who have graduated from Hollywood’s A-List to become storytellers themselves. — Arno

entries.name: Nuremberg
entries.description: Director James Vanderbilt examines the root of evil and the humanity required to combat it in this legal drama starring Russell Crowe and Rami Malek, whose stand-out performances bring to life this devastating period in post-WWII history. — Virginia

entries.name: Christy
entries.description: In the hackneyed parlance of a pugilist, Christy is a knockout that lingers in the ring for one round too many before peekaboo-punching audiences in the guts with a harrowing survival story I won’t spoil in case you aren’t familiar with the real-life bio of boxer Christy Martin. I wasn’t, and the climax left me agog. Sydney Sweeney convincingly bobs in a performance that works so well because of writer/director David Michôd’s subtle skill of loading all the hurt and rage of the real Christy behind Sweeney’s doe-eyes. Life’s incessant body-blows back her into a corner, until she explodes forth with the pent-up anger of a caged animal. Ben Foster could also earn his own much-deserved awards buzz, unless audiences are too repulsed by what might be his most detestable villain role yet. Still, you gotta admire the guy for never shying away from a heel turn. — Alex

entries.name: Palm Royale
entries.detail: Season 2 premieres Nov. 12 on Apple TV
entries.description: I’m tuning into “Palm Royale” S2 to see if the South Florida satire gets enough sun on its face this season. For me, Season 1 was a touch wan, but I’m not ready to unplug from Kristin Wiig’s scheme to cement her status among the social elite of late ‘60s Palm Beach. Especially if it turns out Patti Lupone is the scene’s true grand dame, ranking higher than Carol Burnett somehow. There’s such a tightness to the show’s scripts and direction throughout Season 1, I wondered what it would be like if Wiig and company just improvised – but I’m rooting for the comedy to coalesce and fully deliver on its promise. Plus Ricky Martin on TV just works for me. — Arno

entries.name: Last Samurai Standing
entries.description: Prepare yourself for epic historical action with Netflix’s new series about a group of warriors in a lethal competition. Adapted from Imamura Shogo’s novel “Ikusagami,” the Netflix original follows an ensemble cast as they fight to win ¥100 billion by taking down their fellow contestants as they race from Kyoto to Tokyo. Director Fujii Michihito has promised viewers a six-episode spectacle, “pushing the boundaries of visual storytelling” with massive fight sequences, including one that took more than 1,000 cast and crew members to create. — Adrienne

entries.name: The Running Man
entries.description: Reality TV was an alien concept in the late ‘80s as The Running Man became a VHS cult classic. Releasing a remake in the current climate feels less sci-fi, more actual-real world. Though to some, the movie might have weird mouthfeel, like a pop manifesto squirted over a popcorn tub. To others: Glen Powell sure looks good in a tight uniform. No doubt director Edgar Wright will deliver stylized action while Powell tries to avoid becoming the latest victim on America’s #1 reality elimination show. But sci-fi remakes are always a dicey proposition, and it’s been a minute since a Stephen King adaptation was a smash (though The Monkey will be in my top five of ‘25). — Arno

entries.name: Keeper
entries.description: Who the hell knows what to expect from Osgood Perkin’s next flick. The emerging master of horror has been on a roll pumping out two box office hits in as many years. But while Longlegs was vibey and The Monkey was insane, I suspect Perkins is headed in yet another direction with his sixth feature film. Billed as “A Dark Trip,” Keeper appears to lean into the director’s passion for surrealism as actress Tatiana Maslany deals with her demons — both literal and metaphorical — in a secluded cabin in the woods. — Adrienne

entries.name: The Carpenter's Son
entries.description: If you’re unsure what to make of this new Nicolas Cage horror movie, you’re not alone. Writer-director Lotfy Nathan based his feature on the Infancy Gospel of Thomas,” which details Jesus’ childhood in Egypt. But unlike the more popular biblical tales, this apocryphal text tells more disturbing stories of a young Jesus as he attempts to harness his powers with wondrous and terrible results. Noah Jupe and FKA Twigs play the other members of the Carpenter’s family, and while we’re still not sure how seriously this movie plans to take itself, we’re definitely interested to see where religious horror is headed in anno domini 2025. — Adrienne

entries.name: Landman
entries.description: Landman continues creator Taylor Sheridan's tradition of gritty, character-driven storytelling with high-stakes negotiation, family drama, and power struggles. Call it a guilty pleasure if you must — we are all in. Season 2 picks up with ongoing tension at M-Tex Oil. Tommy Norris (Billy Bob Thornton) faces mounting challenges at work and home, especially from Cami Miller (Demi Moore), who plays a more prominent role this season. Legendary actor Sam Elliott joins the cast as Tommy’s father, introducing new family dynamics. New episodes will drop every Sunday. — Jessica

entries.name: The Mighty Nein
entries.description: With The Mighty Nein premiering this month, Season 4 of Critical Role kicking off in October, and a fourth season renewal of The Legend of Vox Machina, 2025 has been a stellar year for Critical Role fans. Set 20 years after the events of Vox Machina, the new animated series follows a group of fugitives and outcasts who must learn to work together to save the realm and stop reality itself from unraveling. The first three episodes launch on November 19, followed by one new episode each week. Is it Wednesday yet?  —Vanessa

entries.name: Wicked: For Good
entries.description: Millions of people are breathlessly anticipating Wicked’s second act, which touches down almost exactly one year from the first movie. Variety is reporting first reactions for the highly anticipated follow-up are overwhelmingly positive, with early audiences calling it next level, praising the performances, and clamoring for repeat viewings. Director Jon M. Chu claims there are some surprises in store, even for the most die-hard fans of the book and stage play. One surprise we don't have to wait for is the addition of Colman Domingo, who will voice the Cowardly Lion alongside the A-list returning cast. — Adrienne

entries.name: Sisu: Road to Revenge
entries.description: Director Jelmari Helander's original Sisu was hailed as Finland's John Wick, filled with violent set pieces, gorgeous landscapes, and a stoic performance from the weathered Jorma Tommila as a gold prospector hunting down Nazis. A sequel could have just been more of the same, but Helander (whose evil Santa Claus flick Rare Exports is a must-watch) decided to crank the action dial to bananas with some over-the-top sequences and an exceptionally evil Stephen Lang (Avatar, Don't Breathe) serving as a foil to Tommila's silent Aatami. — James

entries.name: Stranger Things
entries.description: It’s been nearly a decade since we first tuned in to watch the story of a missing boy, a strange little girl, and the brave friends who risked everything to help them. Since that first season in 2016, we’ve followed along as Elle and the gang took on everything from demogorgons and the Mind Flayer to high school bullies and even the Russians. But all things must come to an end, and this fall the citizens of Hawkins, Indiana, must finally come together to take on a darkness more deadly than anything before. Expect “big reveals” about the Upside Down, a full return of the main cast, plus the introduction of Linda Hamilton (Terminator, Children of the Corn) as the villainous Dr. Kay, a government agent hell-bent on hunting down Eleven. If you’re feeling a bit raw about the end of the “Stranger Things” era, take heart. The fifth and final season is being released in three volumes that drop Nov. 26, Dec. 25, and Dec. 31, and will include at least two movie-length episodes. — Adrienne

entries.name: Zootopia 2
entries.description: We can't believe it's been almost a decade since Zootopia took the world by storm, becoming one of the biggest hits of the year with over $1 billion at the worldwide box office. In Zootopia 2, beloved duo Judy Hopps (Ginnifer Goodwin) and Nick Wilde (Jason Bateman) return for another adventure, this time investigating a mysterious reptilian newcomer who throws their mammalian metropolis into chaos. In addition to Shakira reprising her role as the Zootopian popstar Gazelle, comedian Fortune Feimster and Oscar winner Ke Huy Quan join the cast. — Vanessa

entries.name: Eternity
entries.description: It’s Albert Brooks’ Defending Your Life meets Celine Song’s Past Lives (Defending Your Past Lives?) as a recently-deceased Elizabeth Olsen struggles to choose whether she spends eternity with her first love (Callum Turner), or her husband (Miles Teller), while the lovers’ triangle fumbles through the sumptuous production design of a mid-century modern limbo. Olsen and her plucky Afterlife Coordinators, played by Da’Vine Joy Randolph and John Early, are too much fun in this funny, charming, and slighly too long romantic comedy.  — Alex

entries.name: It: Welcome to Derry
entries.description: Something bad is coming for the residents of Derry in this prequel series to Andy Muschietti’s IT films that may uncover the origins of Pennywise the dancing clown. Jovan Adepo (“Three Body Problem”) and Taylour Paige (Zola) star as a couple whose recent move to the small Maine town is complicated when a young boy goes missing. Developed for TV by Muschietti, alongside his creative partner and sister Barbara, “IT: Welcome to Derry” is based on the interlude chapters from Stephen King’s novel, which reveal the town’s sordid history and Pennywise’s 27-year cycle of terror. — Adrienne

entries.name: Nobody Wants This
entries.description: Put down your ice cream — the wait for Season 2 is over. Following an irresistible 10-episode debut featuring undeniable onscreen chemistry between leads Adam Brody and Kristen Bell, fans clamored for more, and creator Erin Foster is delivering. I'm thrilled by the news that Jackie Tohn has been promoted to series regular, and excited by the announced roster of guest stars, including Brody's real-life wife Leighton Meester (as Joanne's middle school nemesis, Abby), plus Miles Fowler, Arian Moayed, Alex Karpovsky, Seth Rogen, and Kate Berlant. What truly hooked me about Season 1? The perfect soundtrack, which promises to kill it again with featured artists including Selena Gomez, Role Model, Royel Otis, and more providing the music for Season 2. — Hannah

entries.name: Bugonia
entries.description: Emma Stone and Jesse Plemons are predictably superb in the latest collab with Yorgos Lanthimos’ remake of Jang Joon-hwan’s Save the Green Planet! The director’s use of bleak humor, violence, and plot curveballs won’t be everyone’s cup of tea. But the acting is top-notch, including an adorably sweet performance from Aidan Delbis, who adds a welcome heart to the pitch black satire. — James

plotText.plainText: A young Predator outcast from his clan finds an unlikely ally on his journey in search of the ultimate adversary.
Follows the most miserable person on Earth and the one who must save the world from happiness.

Grace, a writer and young mother, is slowly slipping into madness. Locked away in an old house in and around Montana, we see her acting increasingly agitated and erratic, leaving her companion, Jackson, increasingly worried and helpless.
A WWII psychiatrist evaluates Nazi leaders before the Nuremberg trials, growing increasingly obsessed with understanding evil as he forms a disturbing bond with Hermann Göring.
Tells the story of Christy Martin, the most successful female boxer of the 90s.
An ambitious woman schemes to secure her seat at America's most exclusive table: Palm Beach high society, circa 1969.

In 1878, 292 samurais gather for a battle royale lured by a 100 billion yen prize. Wooden tags are given, last survivor reaching Tokyo wins. Shujiro Saga participates to save his sick family. A dangerous game of survival unfolds on journey
A man joins a game show where contestants, allowed to go anywhere in the world, are pursued by "hunters" hired to kill them.
A romantic anniversary trip to a secluded cabin turns sinister when a dark presence reveals itself, forcing a couple to confront the property's haunting past.
Family hiding in Roman Egypt. Son known as 'the Boy' doubts guardian 'the Carpenter', rebelling with mysterious powers. As he uses abilities, they face natural and divine horrors.
A modern-day tale of fortune seeking in the world of West Texas oil rigs.
Follows a group of criminals and misfits who are the only ones that can prevent the kingdom from plunging into chaos when an arcane artifact capable of reshaping reality falls into the wrong hands.

plotText.plainText: A man returns to dismantle his family's house, where they were murdered in war, to rebuild it elsewhere. When the killer, a Red Army commander, tracks him down, a brutal cross-country pursuit begins.
In 1980s Indiana, a group of young friends witness supernatural forces and secret government exploits. As they search for answers, the children unravel a series of extraordinary mysteries.
Brave rabbit cop Judy Hopps and her friend, the fox Nick Wilde, team up again to crack a new case, the most perilous and intricate of their careers.

In an afterlife where souls have one week to decide where to spend eternity, Joan is faced with the impossible choice between the man she spent her life with and her first love, who died young and has waited decades for her to arrive.
In 1962, a couple with their son move to Derry, Maine just as a young boy disappears. With their arrival, very bad things begin to happen in the town.
An agnostic sex podcaster and a newly single rabbi fall in love; discovering if their relationship can survive their wildly different lives and meddling families.
Two conspiracy-obsessed young men kidnap the high-powered CEO of a major company, convinced that she is an alien intent on destroying planet Earth.
